- The chemical agencies of water<lb/>
&amp; of air so obvious in these cases<lb/>
are in many instances assisted,<lb/>
there is great reason to believe<lb/>
by the operation of Electrical powers. -<lb/>
Under all common circumstances, the<lb/>
atmosphere is Electrical. If a School<lb/>
boy's Kite be raised even in a clear<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="13"
                xml:id="pb-13"
                facs="#i13"/>
            <lb/>
13<lb/>
4<lb/>
blue sky, having a card containing<lb/>
metal attached to it, marks of Electricity<lb/>
will be usually exhibited, &amp; the effect<lb/>
is much more distinct when Clouds are<lb/>
present &amp; there is a Law of Electricity<lb/>
by which all surfaces contiguous to<lb/>
electrified bodies gain an opposite<lb/>
Electricity<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Instance</hi>.<lb/>
And Electricity is a great agent of Chemical<lb/>
change. This is exemplified in the<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag81"
                ref="#chemical_161"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag81">
          Voltaic
          
        </term>
            </rs> apparatus, &amp; has been explained<lb/>
in the chemical Lectures<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Instance</hi>.<lb/>
So that the surfaces of Rocks in a<lb/>
moist state may undergo change, from<lb/>
the tendency of Electricity to evolve some<lb/>
of their principles &amp; a gradual<lb/>
decay &amp; degradation would result<lb/>
from such an operation. -<lb/>
- |_ It is difficult to discriminate<lb/>
accurately between the effects of all<lb/>
these diversified agencies; &amp; it is only<lb/>
by the minute study of the aspect of<lb/>
Rocks, that fair conclusions can be drawn. -<lb/>
- In the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">same class of Rocks</hi>, a slight<lb/>
variety in species, a minute difference<lb/>
in chemical composition or in texture<lb/>
will exceedingly affect the tendency to be<lb/>
operated on, by the different powers<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="14"
                xml:id="pb-14"
                facs="#i14"/>
            <lb/>
of decomposition. - I have already<lb/>
mentioned, that in general the<lb/>
primary Granites, yield of all<lb/>
rocks the least to the operation of<lb/>
the external elements - &amp; suffer<lb/>
in the lapse of ages, only a slight<lb/>
degradation of surface. but yet<lb/>
I have seen a <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
