                xml:id="ttag88"
                ref="#place_1035"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag88" type="place">
          Fingal
        </name>
            </rs>'s Cave &amp;<lb/>
at the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag89"
                ref="#place_126"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag89" type="place">
          Giant's Causeway
        </name>
            </rs>, from the<lb/>
compactness of texture of the<lb/>
pillars - It wonderfully resists<lb/>
decomposition. &amp; no marks of<lb/>
destruction can be perceived upon it. -<lb/>
Whilst at <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Bengavenee</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <rs xml:id="ttag90" ref="#place_479" type="place">
                  <name xml:id="tag90" type="place">
          Pleskin
        </name>
               </rs>
            </add> where the<lb/>
pillars are looser in their texture,<lb/>
it is in a continued state of<lb/>
degradation.<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Sketch</hi>.<lb/>
Qu: <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag91"
                ref="#place_132"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag91" type="place">
          Fairhead
        </name>
            </rs>. -<lb/>
- Here ruins of Nature appear like<lb/>
ruins of Art. -<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag92" ref="#place_592" type="place">
                  <name xml:id="tag92" type="place">
