            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="15"
                xml:id="pb-15"
                facs="#i15"/>
            <lb/>
- The causes of decomposition, |_ evidently<lb/>
from what has been said,) must be<lb/>
exceedingly influenced by <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Climate</hi>. -<lb/>
And in the temperate regions, a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">great</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">cause</hi>, the inequality of heat<lb/>
becomes almost <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">inefficient</hi>. - Yet<lb/>
in this case even from the height<lb/>
of the mean degree the chemical<lb/>
agents of decay act perhaps more<lb/>
powerfully &amp; sooner or later, by<lb/>
slow but <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">sure operations</hi>, the<lb/>
purposes of Nature are attained. -<lb/>
- The causes of the decomposition<lb/>
of Rocks are wonderfully complex,<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">effects</hi> are exceedingly simple,<lb/>
&amp; the end obvious. - The finely<lb/>
divided matter on the surface becomes<lb/>
a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">soil</hi> - |_ From the decomposing<lb/>
agencies assisted by the force of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Gravitation</hi>, rude precipices &amp; Crags<lb/>
before inaccessible, become gentle<lb/>
slopes |_ &amp; sooner or later the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">surface</hi>
            <lb/>
is prepared to become the abode<lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">vegetable life</hi>.<lb/>
- As soon as the Rock begins to<lb/>
be softened - the seeds of lichens, which<lb/>
are constantly <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">floating in the air</hi>, make<lb/>
it their resting place. Their generations<lb/>
occupy it, till a finely divided Earth<lb/>
is formed, which becomes capable of<lb/>
supporting mosses &amp; heath. -<lb/>
Acted upon by light &amp; heat, these<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="16"
                xml:id="pb-16"
                facs="#i16"/>
            <lb/>
plants drink in the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">dew</hi> &amp; convert<lb/>
the constituent parts of the air into<lb/>
nourishment: - Their death &amp;<lb/>
decay afford food for a more<lb/>
perfect species of vegetable, &amp; at<lb/>
length a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">mould</hi> is formed, in<lb/>
which even the Trees of the Forest<lb/>
can fix <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">their</hi> roots, &amp; which is<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">capable</hi> of rewarding the labours<lb/>
of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">cultivator</hi>. -<lb/>
- The greater part of the surface<lb/>
of the Globe must have become<lb/>
the bed of vegetation, soon after<lb/>
the Epoch of the formation of<lb/>
the Secondary Rocks; |_ but <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">since</hi>
            <lb/>
that period, the materials of soils<lb/>
must have been often changed.<lb/>
&amp; that even in cases when they<lb/>
have remained in their natural<lb/>
state. -<lb/>
- The fertility of Soils is determined<lb/>
in a great measure by climate, by<lb/>
situation &amp; their relation to moisture.<lb/>
And the most productive lands in<lb/>
 different parts of the Globe, &amp; in<lb/>
different latitudes, <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">differ very much</hi>,<lb/>
in composition. -<lb/>
- But in general it may be said<lb/>
in considering their Chemical nature,<lb/>
that the Soils of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
