            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="19"
                xml:id="pb-19"
                facs="#i19"/>
            <lb/>
The variety of Rocks gives use to the<lb/>
variety of soils; &amp; different vegetables<lb/>
grow to the greatest advantage in different<lb/>
mixtures of the Earths. A denser &amp; more<lb/>
compact soil is required for grain, than<lb/>
for bulbous roots; but in the same<lb/>
district, almost all the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>xxxx</unclear>
            </del> varieties<lb/>
occurs. |_ Nature, inexhaustible<lb/>
in her resources, affords ample means<lb/>
of subsistence, to all her living<lb/>
productions. Her combinations are all<lb/>
wonderfully &amp; intelligently designed. -<lb/>
|_ Life is preserved by operations which<lb/>
appear destructive - Order &amp; harmony<lb/>
arise from what at first view appears<lb/>
derangement &amp; confusion. The <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">perfection</hi>
            <lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the Work</hi> is perceived the more<lb/>
it is studied; &amp; it declares in distinct<lb/>
language the power &amp; wisdom of the Author. -<lb/>
            <unclear xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">pause</unclear>
            <lb/>
- |_ By the decomposition of Rocks, Soils<lb/>
are not merely <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">produced</hi>; but are<lb/>
likewise renovated. - |_ From the agency<lb/>
of water, there is often a transportation<lb/>
of the materials of Mountains into vallies<lb/>
&amp; plains. -<lb/>
- Those torrents that are the sources of<lb/>
Rivers generally deposite the materials that<lb/>
they have <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">collected in the Mountains</hi>, on<lb/>
the lower grounds - And whilst their beds<lb/>
in the higher regions are becoming deeper<lb/>
&amp; narrower |_ in the Lowlands they are<lb/>
constantly diminishing in depth, but<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="20"
                xml:id="pb-20"
                facs="#i20"/>
            <lb/>
increasing in extent - |_ by the<lb/>
continual depositions of mountain<lb/>
streams in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Lakes</hi> they gradually<lb/>
diminish in size |_ &amp; wherever accurate<lb/>
observations have been made for a<lb/>
 long course of years, the effect is<lb/>
perfectly distinct. -<lb/>
- The rivers which rise beneath<lb/>
the Glaciers of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag121"
                ref="#place_198"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag121" type="place">
          Switzerland
        </name>
            </rs> are<lb/>
almost uniformly turbid. The immense<lb/>
masses of ice are in a continued state<lb/>
of motion &amp; of change. |_ And from<lb/>
the melting of their lowest parts, a<lb/>
declination or sliding down is produced. -<lb/>
|_ In their progress , there is a constant<lb/>
mechanical attrition of the strata<lb/>
beneath |_ &amp; the stream produced<lb/>
from their thawing is loaded with<lb/>
Earths, &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">stoney matters</hi>, reduced<lb/>
into a state of minute division. -<lb/>
- |_ The <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag122"
                ref="#place_355"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag122" type="place">
          Rhone
        </name>
            </rs> rises below the<lb/>
Glacier, which bears its name &amp;<lb/>
at its origin is turbid; but it<lb/>
becomes clearer in its course, till<lb/>
it receives the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag123"
                ref="#place_945"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag123" type="place">
          Arve
        </name>
            </rs>, which is<lb/>
exceedingly troubled |_ but all their<lb/>
