agency of their <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">roots</hi> they preserve the<lb/>
light &amp; finely divided Earth from being<lb/>
carried away by rains, or scattered by<lb/>
winds - Vegetables likewise<lb/>
accumulate considerable proportions of their<lb/>
inflammable matter from the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag168"
                ref="#chemical_058"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag168">
          Carbonic Acid
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
in the Atmosphere &amp; from water -<lb/>
Trees decaying in their natural state, -<lb/>
from the common directions of currents<lb/>
of air or winds, against the ridge or in<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">front of</hi> Hills and Mountains usually fall<lb/>
with their branches towards the summit -<lb/>
&amp; the power of vegetation to collect &amp;<lb/>
elevate <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">solid matter</hi> is fully shewn<lb/>
in the formation &amp; increase of peat<lb/>
mosses<lb/>
- Amidst the changes produced<lb/>
during the long succession of Ages, in<lb/>
the solid parts of the Earth, there<lb/>
seems to be still the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">same grand</hi>
            <lb/>
relation <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">between them</hi>
            <lb/>
- The small <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">ine</del>qua<del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">l</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">nt</add>ities of solid<lb/>
matter carried into the Sea, seem<del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">s</del>
            <lb/>
to be fully compensated for by the<lb/>
effects of vegetation &amp; of volcanic<lb/>
fires; a subject which will be fully<lb/>
discussed in the next Lecture. -<lb/>
- The waste of degradation<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="28"
                xml:id="pb-28"
                facs="#i28"/>
            <lb/>
in particular districts, is compensated<lb/>
for by <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">increase</hi> &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">elevation</hi> in<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">other regions</hi>. -<lb/>
- Animated Beings even, act<lb/>
in preserving the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Equilibrium</hi>. -<lb/>
Without referring to the labours of<lb/>
Man, <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">civilized</hi> &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">reasoning</hi>, <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">great</hi>
            <lb/>
effects, will be found to be produced<lb/>
by many of the most inferior Classes<lb/>
of living Creatures. -<lb/>
Insect tribes in the bosom of the<lb/>
ocean, insignificant in their individual<lb/>
agencies, are enabled after a blind<lb/>
but <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">wise &amp; wonderfully directed instinct</hi>,<lb/>
to accumulate calcareous matter, &amp;<lb/>
raise it above the waves -<lb/>
And many of the low &amp; fertile Islands<lb/>
under the Tropics are mere rocks<lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Coral</hi> covered by Soil - &amp; in<lb/>
the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag169"
                ref="#place_1395"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag169" type="place">
          Pacific
        </name>
            </rs> Ocean, such Islands<lb/>
are abundant &amp; are said to be<lb/>
constantly increasing. -<lb/>
- In the next Lecture I shall<lb/>
enter further upon the detail<lb/>
of the operations by which the<lb/>
beautiful Cycle of terrestrial events<lb/>
is preserved in an uniform order. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="29"
                xml:id="pb-29"
                facs="#i29"/>
            <lb/>
8<lb/>
29<lb/>
It will be <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">further</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">then</add> seen that whilst the<lb/>
arrangements of Matter are continually modified<lb/>
Its great forms are unalterable . -<lb/>
in the grand Cycle of Events, nothing<lb/>
can be said to be accidental, or without<lb/>
design. -<lb/>
The principles in the Earth, the<lb/>
Sea &amp; the Air are in continued<lb/>
circulation, And their change is<lb/>
constantly made subservient to the<lb/>
permanency of Life. -<lb/>
 "By ceaseless <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">motion</hi>, all that is Subsists:<lb/>
Constant rotation of the unwearied wheel<lb/>
That Nature rides upon - maintains<lb/>
Her health, her beauty, her fertility<lb/>
She dreads a moments pause - and<lb/>
Lives but while she moves. -<lb/>
- <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag170"
                ref="#otherwork_114"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag170">
            Its own Revolvency
        </bibl>
            </rs> upholds the World.<lb/>
Winds from all quarters agitate the Air<lb/>
And fit the limpid element for use<lb/>
Else noxious - Oceans, rivers, lakes &amp; streams,<lb/>
All feel the freshening impulse - All are cleansed<lb/>
By countless undulations." -<lb/>
